and crime commissioners in England]]\n[[Category:People from Stretford]]\n[[Category:Police and crime commissioners of Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Labour Party police and crime commissioners]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) mayors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Manchester Business School]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Rochdale]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Tony Lloyd crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Lloyd in 2017\n\n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]]\n| leader = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]<br />[[Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start = 23 March 2018\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Owen Smith]]\n| successor = [[Louise Haigh]] ''(interim since 6 April 2020)''\n\n| office1 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Scotland]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 19 December 2019\n| term_end1 = 6 April 2020\n| predecessor1 = [[Lesley Laird]]\n| successor1 = [[Ian Murray (Scottish politician)|Ian Murray]]\n\n| office2 = [[Department for Communities and Local Government|Shadow Minister of State <br /> for Housing and Planning]]\n| leader2 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Ruth Cadbury]]\n| successor2 = [[Sarah Jones (politician)|Sarah Jones]]\n| term_start2 = 3 July 2017\n| term_end2 = 18 March 2018\n\n| office3 = [[Mayor of Greater Manchester]]\n| status3 = Interim \n| predecessor3 = [[Cities and Local Government Devolution Act 2016|''Office created'']]\n| successor3 = [[Andy Burnham]]\n| term_start3 = 29 May 2015\n| term_end3 = 8 May 2017\n\n| office4 = [[Greater Manchester Police and Crime Commissioner]]\n| deputy4 = Jim Battle\n| predecessor4 = [[Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011|''Office created'']]\n| successor4 = ''Office abolished''\n| term_start4 = 15 November 2012\n| term_end4 = 8 May 2017\n\n| office5 = [[Chair of the Parliamentary Labour Party]]\n| leader5 = [[Tony Blair]]<br />[[Gordon Brown]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] <small>(Acting)</small><br />[[Ed Miliband]]\n| predecessor5 = [[Ann Clwyd]]\n| successor5 = [[David Watts (politician)|David Watts]]\n| term_start5 = 5 December 2006\n| term_end5 = 15 March 2012\n\n| office6 = [[Minister of State for Foreign Affairs (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Foreign Affairs]]\n| primeminister6 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start6 = 5 May 1997\n| term_end6 = 28 July 1999\n| predecessor6 = [[Jeremy Hanley]]<br />[[Nicholas Bonsor]]\n| successor6 = [[John Battle (politician)|John Battle]]\n\n| office7 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]]\n| term_start7 = 8 June 2017\n| term_end7 = \n| predecessor7 = [[Simon Danczuk]]\n| majority7 = 9,668 (20.4%)\n\n| office8 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Manchester Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Central]]\n| predecessor8 = [[Bob Litherland]]\n| successor8 = [[Lucy Powell]]\n| term_start8 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end8 = 22 October 2012\n\n| office9 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Stretford (UK Parliament constituency)|Stretford]]\n| predecessor9 = [[Winston Churchill (1940\u20132010)|Winston Churchill]]\n| successor9 = [[Boundary commissions (United Kingdom)|''Constituency abolished'']]\n| term_start9 = 9 June 1983\n| term_end9 = 1 May 1997\n\n| birth_name = Anthony Joseph Lloyd<ref name=mp>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/anthony-joseph-lloyd|publisher=politics.co.uk|title=Anthony Joseph Lloyd|accessdate=16 November 2012|date=}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|02|25}}<ref name=mp/>\n| birth_place = [[Stretford]], Lancashire, England\n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]<ref name=mp/>\n| spouse = Judith Ann Tear (m. 1974)\n| relations = Sydney Lloyd (father)<br />Ciceley Boatte (mother){{sfn|Dilworth|Stuart-Jones|2012|p=}}\n| children = 4 {{sfn|Dilworth|Stuart-Jones|2012|p=}}\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Nottingham]]\n| occupation = Politician\n| profession = Former university lecturer<ref name=profile>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/3165/tony-lloyd|publisher=guardian.co.uk|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=20 November 2012|date=|title=Tony Lloyd: Electoral history and profile}}</ref>\n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = {{Official website|https://tonylloyd.org.uk}}\n}}\n'''Anthony Joseph \u2019Tony\u2019 Lloyd''' (born 25 February 1950){{sfn|Dilworth|Stuart-Jones|2012|p=}} is a [[Labour Party (UK)|British Labour Party]] politician who has served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]] since [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]. Between 1983 and 1997, he was [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for [[Stretford (UK Parliament constituency)|Stretford]]. He then represented [[Manchester Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Central]] until 2012. Formerly [[Greater Manchester Police and Crime Commissioner]] between 2012 and 2017, and interim [[Mayor of Greater Manchester]] between 2015 and 2017, Lloyd has served as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]] since 2018.\n\nBorn in [[Stretford]], Lloyd served as a [[Trafford MBC|Trafford]] councillor from 1979 to 1984. In 1983, he was elected Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Stretford (UK Parliament constituency)|Stretford]], representing the constituency until 1997, when the constituency was abolished. He then represented [[Manchester Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Central]]. As an MP, Lloyd was an opposition spokesman between 1987 and 1997, a [[Minister of State]] in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] between 1997 and 1999 and [[Chair of the Parliamentary Labour Party]] from 2006 to 2012. Lloyd continued as a constituency MP until October 2012, when he stepped down to contest the [[2012 England and Wales Police and Crime Commissioner elections|2012 Police and Crime Commissioner elections]] for [[Greater Manchester Police]] area.<ref name=power/> He was elected and assumed the position in November 2012. Lloyd, appointed Interim Mayor of Greater Manchester on 29 May 2015,<sup>[[Mayor of Greater Manchester|[2]]]</sup> announced on 11 February 2016 that he would be running to become the Labour Party candidate in the Greater Manchester mayoral election,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/feb/11/labour-tony-lloyd-greater-manchester-mayoral-bid-devolution|title=Labour's Tony Lloyd announces Greater Manchester mayoral bid|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|date=11 February 2016|website=the Guardian|access-date=5 May 2016}}</ref> but he lost to [[Andy Burnham]],<ref name=\"Guardian_090816\">{{cite news | last = Perraudin | first = Frances | title = Andy Burnham selected as Labour candidate for Greater Manchester mayor  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/aug/09/andy-burnham-selected-labours-candidate-manchester-mayor | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 9 August 2016 }}</ref> before being elected as MP for Rochdale in 2017.\n\nIn 2011, the ''[[Manchester Evening News]]'' listed Lloyd among its 250 Most Influential People in Greater Manchester, describing him as \"a major figure on Labour politics in Greater Manchester\",{{sfn|Jupp|2012|p=41}} and \"the most powerful man in Greater Manchester\" on his election as Police and Crime Commissioner in 2012.<ref name=power>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1593908_introducing-new-police-commissioner-tony-lloyd---the-most-powerful-man-in-greater-manchester|publisher=menmedia.co.uk|title=Introducing new police commissioner Tony Lloyd \u2013 the most powerful man in Greater Manchester?|date=16 November 2012|accessdate=20 November 2012|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]}}</ref> In a directory of MPs produced by ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Andrew Roth]] described Lloyd as \"well informed, thoughtful and realistic regionalist and internationalist\".<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Background and family life==\nLloyd was born in [[Stretford]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news-headlines/74682/labour-police-chief-candidate-launches-rochdale-campaign|publisher=rochdaleonline.co.uk|title=Labour Police Chief candidate launches Rochdale campaign|last=Henrys|first=Colin|date=26 October 2012|accessdate=16 November 2012}}</ref><ref name=wont/> on 25 February 1950,{{sfn|Dilworth|Stuart-Jones|2012|p=}} the fourth of five children of Sydney and Ciceley Lloyd (''n\u00e9e'' Boatte).{{sfn|Dilworth|Stuart-Jones|2012|p=}} He was raised in Stretford,<ref name=wont/> and attended [[Stretford Grammar School|Stretford Grammar School for Boys]], the [[University of Nottingham]] (where he gained a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] degree in Maths in 1972), and [[Manchester Business School]] (where he studied for an MBA degree), before becoming a lecturer in Business Studies at the [[University of Salford]].<ref name=mp/><ref name=wont>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1594073_new-greater-manchester-crime-commissioner-tony-lloyd-i-wont-tell-the-chief-constable-how-to-police|title=New Greater Manchester crime commissioner Tony Lloyd: I won't tell the chief constable how to police|first=Deborah|last=Linton|publisher=menmedia.co.uk|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=19 November 2012|accessdate=19 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nLloyd's father died when he was 13, leaving his mother Ciceley, a staunch supporter of the Labour Party, to shape his values. Lloyd said: \"My mother had friends who died in the [[Spanish Civil War]]. I saw that as a simple battle of good versus evil and in that sense the basic morality of politics was instilled in me. I have always thought if not fighting for what's right and just, then what is politics for?\".<ref name=wont/>\n\nLloyd married Judith Ann Tear in 1974.{{sfn|Dilworth|Stuart-Jones|2012|p=}}<ref name=new/> They have three daughters and a son.{{sfn|Dilworth|Stuart-Jones|2012|p=}}<ref name=new>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1593958_new-police-commissioner-tony-lloyd-backbench-stalwart-not-afraid-to-rock-the-boat|publisher=menmedia.co.uk|title=New police commissioner Tony Lloyd: Backbench stalwart not afraid to rock the boat|date=17 November 2012|accessdate=19 November 2012|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]}}</ref> Lloyd supports [[Manchester United F.C.]], and in March 2011 tabled an [[early day motion]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] for [[Ryan Giggs]] to be knighted.<ref name=new/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1409680_arise_sir_ryan_united_star_giggs_should_be_given_a_knighthood_says_mp|publisher=menmedia.co.uk|title=Arise Sir Ryan: United star Giggs should be given a knighthood, says MP|first=Mike|last=Keegan|date=3 March 2011|accessdate=19 November 2012|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]}}</ref> He has ambitions to become a [[beekeeper]].<ref name=bio/>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Trafford Council===\nLloyd was first elected to public office when he stood as a Labour Party candidate in the [[1979 Trafford Council election]], winning a seat on [[Trafford Metropolitan Borough Council]], representing the [[Clifford (ward)|Clifford]] ward on 4 May 1979 (the day [[Margaret Thatcher]] became [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]]).<ref name=mp/><ref name=wont/> Lloyd remained a Trafford councillor until 1984, rising to the rank of Deputy Labour Leader.<ref name=mp/><ref name=wont/><ref name=new/>\n\n===House of Commons===\nLloyd entered the House of Commons as Member of Parliament for [[Stretford (UK Parliament constituency)|Stretford]] on 9 June 1983, after the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]].<ref name=theywork>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/tony_lloyd/manchester_central?gclid=COqom43K3bMCFerItAodCHMAzg|publisher=theyworkforyou.com|title=Tony Lloyd: Former Labour MP for Manchester Central|accessdate=20 November 2012|work=[[TheyWorkForYou]]}}</ref> He was an [[Whip (politics)|opposition whip]] between 1986 and 1987, and became the opposition spokesman for transport (1987\u20131992), employment (1992\u20131994), the environment (1994\u20131995), and foreign affairs (1995\u20131997).<ref name=profile/>\n\nConstituency boundaries were reformed for the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], and Lloyd was selected for the [[Manchester Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Central]] constituency, where he returned at each subsequent general election through to [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].<ref name=wont/> Following the 1997 general election which returned [[Tony Blair]] as Prime Minister, Lloyd was appointed a junior [[Minister of State]] in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] under [[Robin Cook]],<ref name=wont/> beginning 5 May 1997.<ref name=theywork/> In 1998, an inquiry by the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] into the supply of arms from [[Sandline International]] to Africa during the [[Sierra Leone Civil War]] led to accusations that Lloyd had been dishonest and lacked depth over the trade of illicit weaponry.{{sfn|Waller|Criddle|1999|p=446}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/inquiry-finds-sandline-did-breach-arms-embargo-1159472.html|title=Inquiry finds Sandline did breach arms embargo|publisher=independent.co.uk|work=[[The Independent]]|date=17 May 1998|accessdate=21 November 2012|last=Buncombe|first=Andrew}}</ref> Lloyd's position at the Foreign Office ended in a government reshuffle on 28 June 1999.<ref name=theywork/>\n\nLloyd remained a \"powerful\" [[backbencher]],<ref name=profile/><ref name=new/> and on 5 December 2006 became [[Chair of the Parliamentary Labour Party]] \u2013 a post which leads all Labour MPs, both government and backbench MPs \u2013 by defeating the incumbent, [[Ann Clwyd]] who was perceived as being too close to Blair.<ref name=chair>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6211412.stm|title=Lloyd becomes Labour MPs' chair|date=5 December 2006|accessdate=21 November 2012|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> When he unseated Clwyd, the feud between Blair and [[Gordon Brown]] was much reported<ref name=new/> \u2013 Lloyd, was described by journalist [[Michael White (journalist)|Michael White]] as a \"[[Brownism|Brownite]] ally\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jan/06/gordon-brown-leadership-ballot-call|publisher=guardian.co.uk|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 January 2010|accessdate=24 November 2012|title=Ballot call over Gordon Brown's leadership \u2013 what next?|first=Michael|last=White|authorlink=Michael White (journalist)}}</ref> and Labour advisor [[Jonathan Powell (Labour adviser)|Jonathan Powell]] wrote that Lloyd was a key member of Brown's \"team of henchmen on the Labour backbenches to oppose Tony [Blair]\".{{sfn|Powell|2011|p=123}} Lloyd was a Member of the [[North West Regional Select Committee]] from 4 March 2009 to 11 May 2010.<ref name=profile/> After revelations arising from the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal]], Lloyd was forced to apologise for over-claiming \u00a32,210 in rent on his flat in London, adding it was \"a genuine error\".<ref name=new/> As Chair of the Parliamentary Labour Party, Lloyd wrote to Labour MPs urging them to publish all expenses claims.<ref name=claim>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/14/labour-mps-expenses-publish|work=[[The Guardian]]|agency=Press Association|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=12 November 2012|title=Labour MPs urged to publish all expenses claims now}}</ref>\n\nLloyd voted for [[Bryan Gould]] and [[John Prescott]] respectively in the Labour Party leadership elections of [[1992 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|1992]] and [[1994 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|1994]].{{sfn|Waller|Criddle|1999|p=446}} Although the [[TheyWorkForYou]] political activities website declares that Lloyd \"hardly ever rebels\",<ref name=theywork/> he voted against Labour's national agenda in key areas while an MP.<ref name=new/> Lloyd joined rebel Labour MPs by voting against government policy regarding the [[Iraq War]],<ref name=theywork/> and rebelled against government policy to detain terror suspects for 90 days without trial.<ref name=theywork/> He voted against government policy to introduce student [[tuition fees]],<ref name=theywork/> and as an \"anti-nuclear and anti-war campaigner\",<ref name=new/><ref name=chair/> voted against the renewal or replacement of the [[UK Trident programme]] in 2007.<ref name=theywork/> Lloyd was strongly in favour of and voted for the [[reform of the House of Lords]], the [[Identity Cards Act 2006]], and the [[expansion of London Heathrow Airport]].<ref name=theywork/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?id=uk.org.publicwhip/member/40386&showall=yes#divisions|publisher=publicwhip.org.uk|accessdate=20 November 2012|title=Voting Record \u2013 Tony Lloyd MP, Manchester Central (10367)}}</ref> Lloyd supported the bid for a proposed [[regional casino|supercasino]] for East Manchester, and was furious with the [[House of Lords]] and Gordon Brown for axing the scheme, adding it was \"grossly unfair and outrageous\" and that \"those who kicked it into touch deprived a community with one of the highest levels of unemployment the opportunity to access well paid jobs and proper training\".<ref name=new/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6500859.stm|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|work=[[BBC News]]|title=Lords scupper super-casino plan|date=28 March 2007|accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/politics/s/1315730_tony_blairs_fury_at_gordon_brown_for_scrapping_of_supercasino|publisher=menmedia.co.uk|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=28 September 2010|accessdate=21 November 2012|title=Tony Blair's fury at Gordon Brown for scrapping of super-casino|last=Linton|first=Deborah}}</ref> Lloyd supported the proposed [[Greater Manchester congestion charge]],<ref>{{cite web|date=29 January 2007|accessdate=12 November 2012|last=Osuh|first=Chris|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/234515_mps_split_on_congestion_charging|title=MPs split on congestion charging|publisher=menmedia.co.uk|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1025103/Congestion-charge-green-light-Manchester.html|title=Congestion charge to get the green light in Manchester|publisher=dailymail.co.uk|work=[[The Daily Mail]]|accessdate=21 November 2012|date=9 June 2008}}</ref> and campaigned in its favour in the 2008 referendum on the [[Greater Manchester Transport Innovation Fund]], which was \"overwhelmingly rejected\" by voters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/dec/12/congestioncharging-transport|title=Manchester says no to congestion charging|last=Sturcke|first=James|date=12 December 2008|publisher=guardian.co.uk|work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=12 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nLloyd was the leader of the British delegation to the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]] and one of its Vice-Presidents, a leader of the British delegation to the [[Western European Union]], and leader of the British delegation to the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] (OSCE).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tony4gtrmcr.co.uk/about-tony/|publisher=tony4gtrmcr.co.uk|title=About Tony|accessdate=21 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121128155137/http://tony4gtrmcr.co.uk/about-tony/|archivedate=28 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=belarus>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-12044464|publisher=bbc.co.uk|title='The people of Belarus deserved better' say international observers|date=20 December 2010|accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref> He was head of the OSCE at a time when it was monitoring the [[2010 Belarusian presidential election]], which it denounced as fraudulent; Lloyd said the \"election failed to give Belarus the new start it needed\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-12100765|publisher=bbc.co.uk|date=31 December 2012|accessdate=21 November 2012|title=Belarus closes down OSCE office after poll criticism}}</ref> adding \"the people of Belarus deserved better\".<ref name=belarus/> Lloyd was Chair of the [[Trade Union Group of Labour MPs]] from 2002 to 2012.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmpcc.org.uk/about/who-we-are/the-police-and-crime-commissioner/biography/|publisher=gmpcc.org.uk|title=Tony Lloyd's biography|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/news/content/view/full/119327|publisher=morningstaronline.co.uk|title=Trade unions' MP allies fight 'all-out' Tory assault|date=22 May 2012|accessdate=21 November 2012|last=Bagley|first=Roger}}</ref>\n\nLloyd contributed chapters about [[John Robert Clynes]] and [[George Davy Kelley|George Kelley]], Labour members of parliament for Manchester elected in 1906, to ''Men Who Made Labour'', edited by [[Lord Haworth of Fisherfield|Alan Haworth]] and [[Diane Hayter]],{{sfn|Haworth|Hayter|2006|p=xiii}} and contributed a piece on the future of the Labour Party in the 2011 book, ''[[What next for Labour?|What Next for Labour? Ideas for a new generation]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatnextforlabour.com/contributors/|title=Contributors|accessdate=21 November 2012|publisher=whatnextforlabour.com}}</ref>\n\n===Police and crime commissioner===\n{{see also|Greater Manchester Police and Crime Commissioner}}\n[[File:Tony parade.JPG|thumb|right|Tony Lloyd parading with the [[Greater Manchester Police]] at the 2013 [[Manchester Pride]] festival.]]\n[[File:Tony Lloyd, PCC for Greater Manchester.jpg|thumb|right|Tony Lloyd in 2015]]\n\nLloyd was described by [[Andrew Roth]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' as a \"realistic regionalist\";<ref name=profile/> he supported the creation of the [[Greater Manchester Combined Authority]] in 2011, but disagreed that there should be an elected [[Mayor of Greater Manchester]].<ref name=profile/> On 15 February 2012, Lloyd announced his intention to resign as a member of parliament to stand as a candidate for the directly-elected [[Police and Crime Commissioner]] for Greater Manchester.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/politics/s/1485291_veteran-manchester-central-mp-tony-lloyd-to-stand-for-election-as-greater-manchesters-first-police-commissioner|title=Veteran Manchester Central MP Tony Lloyd to stand for election as Greater Manchester's first police commissioner|date=14 February 2012|accessdate=21 November 2012|last=Linton|first=Deborah|publisher=menmedia.co.uk|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]}}</ref> Lloyd said he was willing to leave the Manchester Central constituency \u2013 a Labour [[safe seat]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/granada/story/2012-11-15/manchester-central-by-election/|publisher=itv.com|title=Manchester Central by-election|date=15 November 2012|accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref> \u2013 for the PCC role because in \"all the years I have been a MP, one of the abiding issues that people raised with me was fear of crime\".<ref name=fight>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20391488|publisher=bbc.co.uk|title=Sir Peter Fahy says Tony Lloyd must 'fight' for Greater Manchester Police|date=9 November 2012|accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref> The resulting [[2012 Manchester Central by-election]] was scheduled for the same November polling day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2012/03/whats-going-on-with-manchester-central/|title=What is going on with Manchester Central?|publisher=labourlist.org|work=[[LabourList]]|date=20 March 2012|accessdate=12 November 2012}}</ref> In the [[2012 England and Wales Police and Crime Commissioner elections|Police and Crime Commissioner elections on 15 November 2012]], Lloyd was elected as the inaugural [[Greater Manchester Police and Crime Commissioner]], winning with 139,437 votes, a share of 51.23% and approximately 7% of the electorate,\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatermanchesterpccelection.org.uk/info/11/results|accessdate=16 November 2012|title=Greater Manchester Police and Crime Commissioner (PCC) Election results|publisher=greatermanchesterpccelection.org.uk}}</ref> prompting the ''[[Manchester Evening News]]'' to quip that he had become \"the most powerful man in Greater Manchester\".<ref name=power/>\n\nAs Police and Crime Commissioner for Greater Manchester, Lloyd is one of the Labour Party's highest-profile commissioners, overseeing one of the largest police services in England and Wales outside of [[Greater London]].<ref name=sham/> He will earn \u00a3100,000 per year, the largest figure of any English or Welsh Police and Crime Commissioner.<ref name=sham/> He is based at [[Salford Civic Centre]] and was required to devise a five-year strategic plan for [[Greater Manchester Police]] and hold Sir [[Peter Fahy]], the force's [[Chief constable]], to account.<ref name=sham>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1593957_new-police-and-crime-commissioner-tony-lloyd-gets-to-work-after-shambolic-election|publisher=menmedia.co.uk|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=17 November 2012|accessdate=20 November 2012|last=Linton|first=Deborah|title=New police and crime commissioner Tony Lloyd gets to work after 'shambolic' election}}</ref> On hearing the news that Lloyd had won the election, Fahy said \"one of the key roles of the PCC was negotiating and influencing the other local authorities, the health service, businesses and other organisations&nbsp;... We will be expecting him to fight for GMP at a national level with the Home Office over resourcing and changes to legislation\".<ref name=fight/> At the end of March 2013, Lloyd published the ''Police and Crime Plan 2013\u20132016'', setting his nine priorities for policing Greater Manchester. These were:<ref name=plan>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmpcc.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/CrimePlan.pdf|publisher=gmpcc.org.uk|title=Police and Crime Plan 2013\u20132016|first=Tony|last=Lloyd|date=March 2013|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n:* Driving down crime\n:* Building and strengthening partnerships\n:* Tackling anti-social behaviour\n:* Protecting vulnerable people\n:* Putting victims at the centre\n:* Maintaining public safety, dealing with civil emergencies and emerging threats\n:* Dealing effectively with terrorism, serious crime and organised criminality \n:* Building confidence in policing services\n:* Protecting the police service\n\nThe plan outlines Lloyd's vision \"for all of us in Greater Manchester to work together to build the safest communities in Britain\".<ref name=plan/>\n\n=== Interim Mayor for Greater Manchester ===\nLloyd was appointed as Interim [[Mayor for Greater Manchester]] on 29 May 2015.<sup>[[Mayor of Greater Manchester|[2]]]</sup> He subsequently announced that he would be running to become the Labour Party's candidate for the [[2017 Greater Manchester mayoral election|2017 Greater Manchester Mayoral Elections]] on 11 February 2016.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nOn 9 August [[Andy Burnham]] was selected with 51.1% of the vote. Lloyd placed second with 29.1%.<ref name=\"Guardian_090816\" />\n\n=== Return to the Commons ===\nIn May 2017, Lloyd was selected to stand as the Labour Party's parliamentary candidate for [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]] at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]]. He was selected after the incumbent MP, Simon Danzcuk, was disallowed from standing again as the Labour candidate, owing to an ongoing internal party investigation into Danzcuk's personal conduct.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Syal | first1 = Rajeev | last2 = Stewart | first2 = Heather | title = Simon Danczuk could stand against Labour after quitting party | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/08/labour-tony-lloyd-rochdale-seat-simon-danczuk | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 8 May 2017}}</ref> Lloyd was elected with a majority of 14,819.<ref>{{cite web | title = Election 2017: Rochdale Parliamentary constituency results | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170609130250/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000897 | archive-date = 9 June 2017 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000897 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 8 June 2017 | access-date = 5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2017 he was appointed by Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as a Shadow Housing Minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsocialist.org.uk/reshuffle-2-the-ma/|title=Reshuffle 2: The Maintenance of the Malcontents|date=5 July 2017|work=New Socialist.|access-date=10 July 2017}}</ref>\nOn 23 March 2018, Lloyd received a promotion and became [[Shadow Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]], replacing the sacked [[Owen Smith]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-43521321|title=Jeremy Corbyn sacks Labour frontbencher over referendum call|date=23 March 2018|work=BBC|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, he became the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Scotland]], replacing [[Lesley Laird]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18112487.labour-mp-rochdale-announced-new-scottish-shadow-secretary/|title=Labour MP for Rochdale announced new shadow Secretary for Scotland|website=The National}}</ref> Upon [[Keir Starmer]]'s election as Labour leader Lloyd was replaced in this post by [[Ian Murray (Scottish politician)|Ian Murray]] but continued to be the Shadow Secretary of State for Northern Ireland. [[Louise Haigh]] replaced him on an interim basis in April 2020 after he was admitted to hospital with [[coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/06/ed-miliband-returns-to-labour-frontbench-in-keir-starmer-reshuffle|title=Ed Miliband returns to Labour frontbench in Keir Starmer reshuffle|work=The Guardian|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|date=6 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|title=International Year Book and Statesmen's Who's Who including Who's Who in Public International Law|last2=Stuart-Jones|first2=Megan|publisher=Brill|year=2012|ref=harv|first1=Jennifer|last1=Dilworth}}\n* {{cite book|title=Men Who Made Labour: The Parliamentary Labour Party of 1906 \u2013 the Personalities and the Politics|last2=Hayter|first2=Dianne|publisher=Routledge|year=2006|isbn=9781845680473|ref=harv|first1=Alan|last1=Haworth}}\n* {{cite book|title=250 of the Most Influential People in Greater Manchester|last=Jupp|first=Adam|date=April 2012|publisher=MEN Media|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=The New Machiavelli: How to Wield Power in the Modern World|last=Powell|first=Jonathan|publisher=Random House|year=2011|isbn=9780099546092|ref=harv|authorlink=Jonathan Powell (Labour adviser)}}\n* {{cite book|title=Almanac of British Politics|last2=Criddle|first2=Byron|publisher=Routledge|year=1999|isbn=9780415185417|edition=6th|ref=harv|first1=Robert|last1=Waller}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://tonylloyd.org.uk}}\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = tony-lloyd/450 | hansard = mr-tony-lloyd | hansardcurr = 1537 | guardian = 