K, MH, OD\n|-\n|2\n| {{flagicon|Kuala Lumpur}} [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n|53\n| AK, MH\n|-\n|3\n| {{flagicon|Sabah}} [[Sandakan]], Sabah\n|14\n| MH\n|-\n|4\n| {{flagicon|Brunei}} [[Bandar Seri Begawan]], Brunei\n|6\n| BI\n|-\n|5\n| {{flagicon|Johor}} [[Johor Bahru]], Johor\n|4 \n| AK\n|-\n|6\n| {{flagicon|Indonesia}} [[Tarakan]], Indonesia\n|3\n| MH\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Aviation}}\n* [[Indonesia\u2013Malaysia confrontation]]\n* [[Far East Air Force (Royal Air Force)]]\n* [[List of former Royal Air Force stations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tawau Airport}}\n*[http://www.malaysiaairports.com.my/index.php?ch=17&pg=55&ac=184 Tawau Airport, Sabah] at [[Malaysia Airports|Malaysia Airports Holdings Berhad]]\n*{{NWS-current|WBKW}}\n*{{ASN|TWU}}\n\n{{Airports in Malaysia}}\n{{Buildings and structures in Sabah}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tawau]]\n[[Category:Airports in Sabah]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Tawau Airport\n| nativename = <small>''Lapangan Terbang Tawau''</small>\n| nativename-a =\n| image = Tawau Airport.jpg\n| caption = \n| IATA = TWU\n| ICAO = WBKW\n| type = Public\n| owner = [[Government of Malaysia]]\n| operator = [[Malaysia Airports|Malaysia Airports Holdings Berhad]]\n| city-served = [[Tawau Division]]\n| location = [[Tawau]], [[Sabah]], [[Malaysia]]\n| hub =  \n| timezone = [[Time in Malaysia|MST]]\n| utc = [[UTC+08:00]]\n| elevation-f = 57\n| coordinates = {{coord|04|18|48|N|118|07|19|E|region:MY-12|display=it}}\n| website =\n| image_map = LocationMalaysia.svg\n| image_map_caption = [[Sabah]] state in Malaysia\n| pushpin_map = Malaysia East#Borneo#Malaysia#Southeast Asia#Asia\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in [[East Malaysia]]\n| pushpin_label = \n'''TWU''' /WBKW\n| r1-number = 06/24\n| r1-length-m = 2,685\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| metric-rwy = y\n| stat1-header = Passenger\n| stat1-data = 1,642,171 ({{increase}} 19.4%)\n| stat-year = 2018\n| footnotes = Sources: official web site<ref name=MAHB>[http://www.malaysiaairports.com.my/index.php?ch=38&pg=157&ac=1039 Tawau Airport, Sabah] at [[Malaysia Airports Holdings Berhad]]</ref><ref name=AIP>[http://aip.dca.gov.my/aip%20pdf/AD/AD2/WBKW/WBKW-Tawau.pdf WBK - TAWAU] at Department of Civil Aviation Malaysia</ref>\n| stat2-header = Airfreight (tonnes)\n| stat2-data = 4,060 ({{increase}} 4.5%)\n| stat3-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat3-data = 15,579 ({{increase}} 20.3%)\n}}\n\n'''Tawau Airport''' ({{lang-ms|Lapangan Terbang Tawau}}) {{airport codes|TWU|WBKW}} is an airport located {{Convert|15|NM|lk=in}} north east<ref name=AIP/> of [[Tawau]], [[Sabah]], [[Malaysia]]. It is one of two airports in Sabah with immigration counters for international flights, the other being [[Kota Kinabalu International Airport]]. Tawau Airport serves the districts of [[Tawau]], [[Kunak]] and [[Semporna]] and is the nearest airport to the diving islands of [[Sipadan]], [[Mabul]] and [[Kapalai]], all of which are located in the latter district.\n\n==Old Airport==\nThe old Tawau Airport was located on Jalan Utara (Malay for 'Northern Road'), about {{Convert|2|mi|abbr=on}} outside Tawau. It was officially opened in 1968 by the then Transport Minister of Malaysia, [[Sardon Haji Jubir|Tan Sri Haji Sardon]]. It could only cater to small aircraft such as the [[Fokker 27]].\n\nBy the early 80s, the airport received its first Boeing 737 flight operated by Malaysia Airlines following the newly extended runway. In the 90s, the airport also witnessed regional international destinations to [[Tarakan]], [[Balikpapan]] and [[Makassar]] in Indonesia by [[Bouraq Indonesian Airlines]] and [[Merpati Nusantara Airlines]] due to the close socio-economic ties between Tawau and the main eastern Indonesian urban areas.\n\nOn 15 September 1995, [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 2133]], a flight from Kota Kinabalu operated by a Fokker 50 aircraft, touched down {{Convert|500|m|abbr=on}} before the end of the {{Convert|2200|m|abbr=on|0}}-long runway. While attempting a go-around, the aircraft crashed into a shantytown known as Kampung Seri Menanti.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-09-16/news/9509160526_1_shantytown-plane-overshoots-runway-tawau|title=Plane Overshoots Runway, Crashes, Killing 34 People|date=16 September 1995|accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref> There were 34 fatalities, including two crewmembers.<ref>[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19950915-0 Aircraft accident Fokker 50 9M-MGH Tawau Airport (TWU) on 15 Sep 1995]</ref> In October 2001, another Malaysia Airlines flight (this one operated by a Boeing 737-400) skidded off the runway without causing any injuries or fatalities.\n\nA survey found that the old Tawau Airport had one of the shortest runways in Malaysia. The airport's runway would need to be extended (or a new airport built) to safely accommodate larger aircraft. In view of this, the government announced plans to construct a new airport to be located in the Balung area, approximately {{Convert|30|km|abbr=on}} east of downtown Tawau along the [[Malaysia Federal Route 13 (Sabah)|Tawau \u2013 Semporna highway]].\n\n==Present==\nThe new Tawau Airport was opened to the public in December 2001. In 2003, it was officially opened by the then Transport Minister of Malaysia, Tun Dr. [[Ling Liong Sik]]. With a capacity of over 1.4 million passengers per annum, it is the second largest airport in Sabah after Kota Kinabalu International Airport. AirAsia added an international destination to [[Changi Airport|Singapore]] in 2010 and to [[Kuching Airport|Kuching]] in the Malaysian state of Sarawak in 2018, although both were discontinued due to low passenger yields. In 2018, 1,642,171 passengers passed through the airport and there were 15,579 aircraft movements.<ref name=MAHB />\n\nAt present, Tawau Airport has a {{Convert|2685|x|47|m|abbr=on|0}}-long runway, namely runway 06/24. Runway 24 is equipped with Instrument Landing System (ILS). The {{frac|1|1|2}}-storey terminal building is equipped with two aerobridges. The airport can accommodate eight aircraft at any given time, and its car park can accommodate 500 vehicles. In addition, there is a police station opposite the terminal building.\n\nIn 2019, Tony Fernandes, the CEO of AirAsia Group is planning to connect Tawau with direct flight services to several cities in China, Korea, Japan and other Asean cities by 2020 due to its proximity with [[Tun Sakaran Marine Park]], [[Mabul]], [[Sipadan]] island, [[Maliau Basin]], [[Danum Valley]] and other major ecotourism sites in southeast Sabah.<ref>[http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/141859/international-airasia-flights-to-s-kan-and-tawau-early-next-year/ International AirAsia flights to S\u2019kan and Tawau early next year]</ref> The airport also witnessed an additional international destination from [[Bandar Seri Begawan]] by RB Link in November 2019 and followed by charter flights to [[Guangzhou]] by Hainan Airlines by 2020. Correlating with the development, the Sabah Tourism Board has signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) to promote both Royal Brunei Airlines and Tawau for its marketing campaign in the United Kingdom.<ref>[http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/143212/tawau-s-first-global-air-access-starts/ Tawau\u2019s first global air access starts]</ref>\n\nThe airport is also slated for a further expansion after recording 1.64 million passengers in 2018, overreaching its original capacity of 1.4 million users. With 19.4% growth in 2018, it is the fourth in terms of passenger growth in the country (after Kuala Lumpur, Kota Kinabalu and Penang International Airport).<ref name=\"theborneopost.com GZ\">https://www.theborneopost.com/2019/06/28/guangzhou-tawau-direct-flights-to-start-january-2020/</ref> The expansion is expected to commenced by the end of 2019 and will include upgrading existing facilities together with a better shopping experience.<ref name=\"theborneopost.com GZ\"/>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n[[File:Tawau Sabah TawauAirport-01.jpg|thumb|One of Tawau Airport's two [[aerobridge]]s, mainly used by Malaysia Airlines and Malindo Air.]]\n{{Airport-dest-list\n| [[AirAsia]] | [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]], [[Kota Kinabalu International Airport|Kota Kinabalu]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n| [[Malaysia Airlines]] | [[Kota Kinabalu International Airport|Kota Kinabalu]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n| [[Malaysia Airlines]] <br>operated by [[MASwings]] | [[Sandakan Airport|Sandakan]], [[Juwata International Airport|Tarakan]]\n| [[Malindo Air]] | [[Kota Kinabalu International Airport|Kota Kinabalu]],<ref>[https://www.malindoair.com/promo/Hello-Tawau Hello Tawau]</ref> [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]] <ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Malindo Air 1Q20 Domestic network addition |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/288977/malindo-air-1q20-domestic-network-addition/ |website=Routesonline}}</ref>\n| [[RB Link]] <br>operated by [[Malindo Air]] for [[Royal Brunei Airlines]] | [[Brunei International Airport|Bandar Seri Begawan]]<ref>[http://www.bernama.com/state-news/berita.php?id=1788573 Royal Brunei now flies to Tawau]</ref>\n}}\n\n===Cargo===\n{{airport-dest-list\n|[[AsiaCargo Express]]|[[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]}}\n\n==Traffic and statistics==\n\n===Traffic===\n{|class=\"toccolours sortable\" style=\"padding:0.5em;\"\n|+ '''Annual passenger numbers and aircraft statistics\n|-\n! | <center>Year</center>\n! | <center>Passengers</center><br /><center>handled</center>\n! | <center>Passenger</center><br /><center>% Change</center>\n! | <center>Cargo</center><br /><center>(tonnes)</center>\n! | <center>Cargo</center><br /><center>% Change</center>\n! | <center>Aircraft</center><br /><center>Movements</center>\n! | <cente