m/teams/juventus Juventus F.C.] at [[Serie A]] {{in lang|en|it}}\n* [http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/teams/club=50139/profile/index.html Juventus F.C.] at [[UEFA]]\n* [https://www.fifa.com/live-scores/clubs/club=italy-juventus-31085/index.html Juventus F.C.] at [[FIFA]]\n\n{{Juventus F.C.}}\n{{Navboxes|titlestyle = background:#000;border:1px solid gold;color:#fff;|list1=\n{{Serie A}}\n{{Football in Italy}}\n{{Original Italian Serie A clubs}}\n{{Italian Championship winners}}\n{{Coppa Italia winners}}\n{{Supercoppa Italiana winners}}\n{{UEFA Champions League winners}}\n{{UEFA Cup Winners' Cup winners}}\n{{UEFA Europa League winners}}\n{{UEFA Intertoto Cup winners}}\n{{UEFA Super Cup winners}}\n{{Intercontinental Cup winners}}\n{{ECA}}\n{{G-14}}\n{{EXOR}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Juventus F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:1897 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1897]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Borsa Italiana]]\n[[Category:Coppa Italia winning clubs]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Italy]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Piedmont and Aosta Valley]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Turin]]\n[[Category:G-14 clubs]]\n[[Category:Italian football First Division clubs]]\n[[Category:Publicly traded sports companies]]\n[[Category:Serie A winning clubs]]\n[[Category:Serie A clubs]]\n[[Category:Serie B clubs]]\n[[Category:Sport in Turin]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning clubs]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning clubs]]\n", "name_user": "Nehme1499", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOut on loan", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juventus_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Friendship Nine", "text_new": "The '''Friendship Nine''', or '''Rock Hill Nine''',<ref>{{cite news |title=The Friendship Nine / January 31, 1961 |author= |newspaper=Herald Online |date=February 22, 2004 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/heraldonline/access/550272941.html?dids=550272941:550272941&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+22%2C+2004&author=Brittany+Rawlinson%2C+junior%2C+Northwestern+High+School&pub=Herald+Online&desc=The+Friendship+Nine+%2F+January+31%2C+1961&pqatl=google |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=They were students at Friendship College and called themselves the Friendship Nine. The members of this group were James Wells, William \"Dub\" Massey, Robert McCullough, John Gaines, William \"Scoop\" Williamson, Willie McLeod, Thomas Gaither, Clarence Graham, Charles Taylor and Mack Workman. }}</ref> was a group of African-American men who went  to jail after staging a [[sit-in]] at a segregated [[McCrory's]] [[lunch counter]] in [[Rock Hill, South Carolina]] in 1961. The group gained nationwide attention because they followed the 1960 [[Nashville sit-in]] strategy of \"Jail, No Bail\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Associated Press\u2019Sing-In\u2019 Negroes Eat Hearty; Say \u2018Jail\u2014No Bail\u2019 |author=Associated Press |newspaper=The Spartanburg Herald |date=February 21, 1961 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=g3ssAAAAIBAJ&sjid=acwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7405,2802776&dq=rock+hill+sit-in&hl=en |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=Eight Negro Demonstrators is a disciplinary cell at the York County Prison Camp accepted and ate second helpings Monday of the full meal given every third day to prisoners on bread and water. }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Scoggins |first=Michael, Rawlinson David |title=Rock Hill, Jail No Bail & The Friendship Nine |url=http://www.friendshipcollege.org/jailnobail.html |publisher=Friendship Jr. College 445 Allen St. Rock Hill, South Carolina |accessdate=21 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117063355/http://www.friendshipcollege.org/jailnobail.html |archivedate=17 November 2011 }}\"(..) The first man tried was Charles Taylor, the Friendship student from New Jersey. Taylor was tried, found guilty, convicted, and sentenced to $100 fine or 30 days hard labor on the York County Prison Farm. The protesters' attorney, an African-American lawyer from Sumter named Ernest A. Finney, then asked the judge to let Taylor's trial be used as a basis for the other nine and the judge agreed. The other nine were then tried, found guilty, and sentenced to the same punishment. Taylor was concerned about possibly losing his athletic scholarship at Friendship, so with the assistance of the NAACP, he paid his bail and was released. The NAACP offered to pay the bail for the remaining nine protesters but they refused, and on February 2, they began serving out their 30-day sentences on the county prison farm. After beginning their sentence on the county farm, the nine protesters were quickly given the appellation \"Friendship Nine\" by the press, and the case became famous nationwide. Motorcades of other protesters and supporters converged on the prison, and members of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) came to Rock Hill and demonstrated; they too were arrested, jailed and refused bail. Over the course of the next year further demonstrations and arrests followed in Rock Hill, as well as in other cities throughout the United States. Protesters across the country adopted the \"jail no bail\" policy implemented by the Friendship Nine, and served out their jail sentences rather than helping to subsidize a system that supported segregation and inequality. These acts of heroism by the Friendship Nine and others helped to spur even larger protests like the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom in August 1963 and the famous march from Selma to Montgomery in March 1965. (..)\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jail, No Bail' Idea Stymied Cities' Profiting From Civil Rights Protesters|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/social_issues/jan-june11/jail_03-07.html|work=South Carolina ETV's \"Carolina Stories.\"|publisher=The PBS NewsHour|accessdate=21 October 2011}}\"The 'Jail, No Bail' strategy became a new tactic in the fight for civil rights. Documentary produced by South Carolina ETV documenting the key moment in civil rights history.\" (Video and Audio)</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jail, No Bail|url=http://www.scetv.org/index.php/carolina_stories/show/jail_no_bail/|work=Carolina Stories|publisher=South Carolina ETV|accessdate=21 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111219005915/http://www.scetv.org/index.php/carolina_stories/show/jail_no_bail/|archivedate=19 December 2011}}\"(..) In previous sit-ins across the South, protestors were arrested, processed by the police, fined and then released, creating a dubious revenue stream from which many municipalities easily profited. But when the Friendship students went before the judge, they chose to serve their time behind bars.  For the first time, not only did the city not collect its $100 per person, it actually had to pay to house and feed the men. (..) Word of their action spread like wildfire, receiving national media attention, including the New York Times.  The \u201cJail, No Bail\u201d strategy became the new tactic that helped galvanize the civil rights protest movement. (..)\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hartford|first=Bruce|title=Rock Hill SC, \"Jail-No-Bail\" Sit-ins (Feb-Mar)|url=http://www.crmvet.org/tim/timhis61.htm|work=The Civil Rights Movement Veterans|publisher=Westwind Writers Inc.|accessdate=21 October 2011}}\"(..) At the October 1960 SNCC strategy conference in Atlanta, some activists argue for \"Jail-No-Bail\" tactics. They take a Gandhian position that paying bail or fines indicates acceptance of an immoral system and validates their own arrests. And by serving their sentences, they dramatize the injustice, intensify the struggle, and gain additional media coverage. There is also a practical component to \"Jail-No-Bail.\" The Movement has little money and most southern Blacks are poor. It is hard to scrape up bail money, and sit-in struggles are faltering \u2014 not from lack of volunteers to risk arrest \u2014 but from lack of money to bail them out. Moreover, paying fines provides the cops with financial resources that are then used to continue suppressing the freedom struggle. By refusing bail, they render meaningless the no-money-for-bail barrier and by serving time they put financial pressure on local authorities who have to pay the costs of incarcerating them.  (..)\"</ref> which lessened the huge financial burden [[civil rights]] groups were facing as the [[sit-in movement]] spread across the South. They became known as the Friendship Nine because eight of the nine men were students at Rock Hill's [[Friendship Junior College]].\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Greensboro sit-ins|first sit-in]] happened in February 1960 when four black students from [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]] sat down at a segregated [[F.W. Woolworth Company|Woolworth's]] lunch counter in [[Greensboro, North Carolina]]. The movement spread across the South, reaching Rock Hill on Feb. 12, when about 100 black students staged sit-ins at various downtown lunch counters. Over the next year, several sit-ins were held in the city.\n\n==Ongoing demonstrations==\nOn Jan. 31, 1961, students from Friendship Junior College and others picketed McCrorys's on Main Street in Rock Hill to protest the segregated lunch counters at the business. They walked in, took seats at the counter and ordered hamburgers, soft drinks and coffee.<ref>{{cite news |title=Activists revive memories of '60s sit-in |author=Lauren Hoyt / The Herald |newspaper=Herald Online |date=February 2, 2003 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/heraldonline/access/283205511.html?dids=283205511:283205511&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+02%2C+2003&author=Lauren+Hoyt+%2F+The+Herald&pub=Herald+Online&desc=Activists+revive+memories+of+'60s+sit-in&pqatl=google |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=The three men each vividly recounted Jan 31 1961 when they were arrested for a siting at Rock Hill's McCrory's department store and the ensuing 30 days ... }}</ref>\n\nThe next day, 10 were convicted of trespassing and breach of the peace and sentenced to serve 30 days in jail or to pay a $100 fine. One man paid a fine, but the remaining nine \u2014 eight of whom were Friendship students \u2014chose to take the sentence of 30 days hard labor at the York County Prison Farm. Their choosing jail over a fine or bail marked a first in the Civil Rights Movement since the 1960 Nashville sit-ins, and it sparked the \"jail, no bail\" strategy that came to be emulated in other places. A growing number of people<ref>{{cite news |title=Negroes Open New Front |author=Associated Press |newspaper=St. Petersburg Independent |date=February 9, 1961 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hz9QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M1cDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7379,1465317&dq=rock+hill+sit-in&hl=en |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=In Rock Hill, SC, 150 Negroes and a white man staged a mass protest againstnLKNCkSNLasbkfhbajsbdfjAS<MNFCkjaSBFlDfLAJfdADLjfDajfJADsdf:ADb:jfbasljfdsnlv\"acifLJHurt\u2026.Hamm was arrested with the Rev. A.C. Ivory\u2026. }}</ref>\n\n==Prison strikes==\nSince these protestors chose prison instead of bail, they were sent to a work camp, where twice they refused to work, were put on bread and water as punishment.<ref>{{cite news |title=8 Jailed Negroes Put In Solitary; Refuse To Work |author= |newspaper=The Free Lance-Star |date=February 20, 1961 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HvdNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IYsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4432,2889166&dq=rock+hill+sit-in&hl=en |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=Eight Negro students jailed in a Rock Hill, S. C. sit-in demonstration have been placed on bread and water in solitary confinement for what prison officials called a refusal to work. }}</ref>\n\n==The nine==\nIn 2007 the city of Rock Hill unveiled an historic marker honoring the Friendship Nine at a reception honoring the men. At that time, eight of the Friendship Nine were living.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.heraldonline.com/smedia/2007/01/27/15/friendshipnine.source.prod_affiliate.6.mov |title=Historic marker unveiled by Friendship Nine |author=Justin McGuire |date=January 27, 2007 |publisher=Herald Online |accessdate=December 2, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n* Robert McCullough (died on August 7, 2006)\n* John Gaines\n* Thomas Gaither (at the time, he was a field secretary with the [[Congress of Racial Equality]] and was the only one of the nine who was not a Friendship student)\n* Clarence Graham (died on March 25, 2016)\n* Willie Thomas [W.T. \"Dub\"] Massey (is now a Substitute teacher in the Rock Hill area)<ref>{{cite web|last=Dys|first=Andrew|title=Rock Hill civil rights icon tells young people: \u2018Be great\u2019|url=http://www.heraldonline.com/2013/01/18/4553647/friendship-nine-icon-tells-young.html|work=The Rock Hill, SC Herald|publisher=The McClatchy Co|accessdate=15 October 2013}}</ref> \n* Willie McCleod\n* James Wells (died on July 7, 2018<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldonline.com/latest-news/article214550175.html|title='An American hero.' Friendship 9 member and Rock Hill civil rights icon dies|work=heraldonline|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en}}</ref>)\n* David Williamson Jr.\n* Mack Workman\n\n==The significance==\n\"What made the Rock Hill action so timely ... was that it responded to a tactical dilemma that was arising in [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee|SNCC]] discussions across the South: how to avoid the crippling limitations of scarce bail money,\" wrote [[Taylor Branch]] in ''[[America in the King Years|Parting the Waters]],'' his Pulitzer Prize winning account of the Civil Rights Movement. \"The obvious advantage of 'jail, no bail' was that it reversed the financial burden of the protest, costing the demonstrators no cash while obligating the white authorities to pay for jail space and food. The obvious disadvantage was that staying in jail represented a quantum leap in commitment above the old barrier of arrest, lock-up, and bail-out.\"\n\n==Convictions overturned==\nIn 2015, Judge John C. Hayes III (nephew of the original judge who sentenced the Friendship Nine to 30 days jail-time at York County,SC chain-gang) of Rock Hill overturned the convictions of the nine, stating: \"We cannot rewrite history, but we can right history.\" At the same occasion, Prosecutor Kevin Brackett apologized to the eight men still living, who were in court.<ref>{{cite news |author=Mitch Weiss |title=Famed SC civil rights protesters have convictions erased |url=http://www.wjtv.com/story/27958893/famed-sc-civil-rights-protesters-have-convictions-erased |quote= |pages= |work=WJTV News |agency=Associated Press |date=January 2015 |accessdate=2015-01-28 }}</ref> The men were represented at the hearing by [[Ernest A. Finney, Jr.]], the same lawyer who had defended them originally, who subsequently went on to become the first African-American Chief Justice of the [[South Carolina Supreme Court]] since [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Amber Payne |title='Friendship Nine': Convictions Overturned For Famed Civil Rights Protesters |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/nbcblk/friendship-nine-convictions-overturned-famed-civil-rights-protesters-n295291 |quote= |pages= |work=NBC News |agency=Associated Press |date=January 28, 2015 |accessdate=2015-01-28 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://media.heraldonline.com/smedia/2007/01/27/15/friendshipnine.source.prod_affiliate.6.mov Heraldonline video of historic marker ceremony in 2007]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jVGW9JxTJK8 Civil Rights History Project: Thomas Walter Gaither], video 2:11:06, Library of Congress\n\n{{Civil rights movement}} \n\n[[Category:1961 in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:1961 in American politics]]\n[[Category:Civil rights protests in the United States]]\n[[Category:Civil disobedience]]\n[[Category:History of South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Overturned convictions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Rock Hill, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:McCrory Stores]]\n[[Category:History of African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:Lunch counters]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Friendship Nine''', or '''Rock Hill Nine''',<ref>{{cite news |title=The Friendship Nine / January 31, 1961 |author= |newspaper=Herald Online |date=February 22, 2004 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/heraldonline/access/550272941.html?dids=550272941:550272941&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+22%2C+2004&author=Brittany+Rawlinson%2C+junior%2C+Northwestern+High+School&pub=Herald+Online&desc=The+Friendship+Nine+%2F+January+31%2C+1961&pqatl=google |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=They were students at Friendship College and called themselves the Friendship Nine. The members of this group were James Wells, William \"Dub\" Massey, Robert McCullough, John Gaines, William \"Scoop\" Williamson, Willie McLeod, Thomas Gaither, Clarence Graham, Charles Taylor and Mack Workman. }}</ref> was a group of African-American men who went  to jail after staging a [[sit-in]] at a segregated [[McCrory's]] [[lunch counter]] in [[Rock Hill, South Carolina]] in 1961. The group gained nationwide attention because they followed the 1960 [[Nashville sit-in]] strategy of \"Jail, No Bail\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Associated Press\u2019Sing-In\u2019 Negroes Eat Hearty; Say \u2018Jail\u2014No Bail\u2019 |author=Associated Press |newspaper=The Spartanburg Herald |date=February 21, 1961 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=g3ssAAAAIBAJ&sjid=acwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7405,2802776&dq=rock+hill+sit-in&hl=en |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=Eight Negro Demonstrators is a disciplinary cell at the York County Prison Camp accepted and ate second helpings Monday of the full meal given every third day to prisoners on bread and water. }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Scoggins |first=Michael, Rawlinson David |title=Rock Hill, Jail No Bail & The Friendship Nine |url=http://www.friendshipcollege.org/jailnobail.html |publisher=Friendship Jr. College 445 Allen St. Rock Hill, South Carolina |accessdate=21 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117063355/http://www.friendshipcollege.org/jailnobail.html |archivedate=17 November 2011 }}\"(..) The first man tried was Charles Taylor, the Friendship student from New Jersey. Taylor was tried, found guilty, convicted, and sentenced to $100 fine or 30 days hard labor on the York County Prison Farm. The protesters' attorney, an African-American lawyer from Sumter named Ernest A. Finney, then asked the judge to let Taylor's trial be used as a basis for the other nine and the judge agreed. The other nine were then tried, found guilty, and sentenced to the same punishment. Taylor was concerned about possibly losing his athletic scholarship at Friendship, so with the assistance of the NAACP, he paid his bail and was released. The NAACP offered to pay the bail for the remaining nine protesters but they refused, and on February 2, they began serving out their 30-day sentences on the county prison farm. After beginning their sentence on the county farm, the nine protesters were quickly given the appellation \"Friendship Nine\" by the press, and the case became famous nationwide. Motorcades of other protesters and supporters converged on the prison, and members of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) came to Rock Hill and demonstrated; they too were arrested, jailed and refused bail. Over the course of the next year further demonstrations and arrests followed in Rock Hill, as well as in other cities throughout the United States. Protesters across the country adopted the \"jail no bail\" policy implemented by the Friendship Nine, and served out their jail sentences rather than helping to subsidize a system that supported segregation and inequality. These acts of heroism by the Friendship Nine and others helped to spur even larger protests like the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom in August 1963 and the famous march from Selma to Montgomery in March 1965. (..)\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jail, No Bail' Idea Stymied Cities' Profiting From Civil Rights Protesters|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/social_issues/jan-june11/jail_03-07.html|work=South Carolina ETV's \"Carolina Stories.\"|publisher=The PBS NewsHour|accessdate=21 October 2011}}\"The 'Jail, No Bail' strategy became a new tactic in the fight for civil rights. Documentary produced by South Carolina ETV documenting the key moment in civil rights history.\" (Video and Audio)</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jail, No Bail|url=http://www.scetv.org/index.php/carolina_stories/show/jail_no_bail/|work=Carolina Stories|publisher=South Carolina ETV|accessdate=21 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111219005915/http://www.scetv.org/index.php/carolina_stories/show/jail_no_bail/|archivedate=19 December 2011}}\"(..) In previous sit-ins across the South, protestors were arrested, processed by the police, fined and then released, creating a dubious revenue stream from which many municipalities easily profited. But when the Friendship students went before the judge, they chose to serve their time behind bars.  For the first time, not only did the city not collect its $100 per person, it actually had to pay to house and feed the men. (..) Word of their action spread like wildfire, receiving national media attention, including the New York Times.  The \u201cJail, No Bail\u201d strategy became the new tactic that helped galvanize the civil rights protest movement. (..)\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hartford|first=Bruce|title=Rock Hill SC, \"Jail-No-Bail\" Sit-ins (Feb-Mar)|url=http://www.crmvet.org/tim/timhis61.htm|work=The Civil Rights Movement Veterans|publisher=Westwind Writers Inc.|accessdate=21 October 2011}}\"(..) At the October 1960 SNCC strategy conference in Atlanta, some activists argue for \"Jail-No-Bail\" tactics. They take a Gandhian position that paying bail or fines indicates acceptance of an immoral system and validates their own arrests. And by serving their sentences, they dramatize the injustice, intensify the struggle, and gain additional media coverage. There is also a practical component to \"Jail-No-Bail.\" The Movement has little money and most southern Blacks are poor. It is hard to scrape up bail money, and sit-in struggles are faltering \u2014 not from lack of volunteers to risk arrest \u2014 but from lack of money to bail them out. Moreover, paying fines provides the cops with financial resources that are then used to continue suppressing the freedom struggle. By refusing bail, they render meaningless the no-money-for-bail barrier and by serving time they put financial pressure on local authorities who have to pay the costs of incarcerating them.  (..)\"</ref> which lessened the huge financial burden [[civil rights]] groups were facing as the [[sit-in movement]] spread across the South. They became known as the Friendship Nine because eight of the nine men were students at Rock Hill's [[Friendship Junior College]].\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Greensboro sit-ins|first sit-in]] happened in February 1960 when four black students from [[North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University]] sat down at a segregated [[F.W. Woolworth Company|Woolworth's]] lunch counter in [[Greensboro, North Carolina]]. The movement spread across the South, reaching Rock Hill on Feb. 12, when about 100 black students staged sit-ins at various downtown lunch counters. Over the next year, several sit-ins were held in the city.\n\n==Ongoing demonstrations==\nOn Jan. 31, 1961, students from Friendship Junior College and others picketed McCrorys's on Main Street in Rock Hill to protest the segregated lunch counters at the business. They walked in, took seats at the counter and ordered hamburgers, soft drinks and coffee.<ref>{{cite news |title=Activists revive memories of '60s sit-in |author=Lauren Hoyt / The Herald |newspaper=Herald Online |date=February 2, 2003 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/heraldonline/access/283205511.html?dids=283205511:283205511&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+02%2C+2003&author=Lauren+Hoyt+%2F+The+Herald&pub=Herald+Online&desc=Activists+revive+memories+of+'60s+sit-in&pqatl=google |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=The three men each vividly recounted Jan 31 1961 when they were arrested for a siting at Rock Hill's McCrory's department store and the ensuing 30 days ... }}</ref>\n\nThe next day, 10 were convicted of trespassing and breach of the peace and sentenced to serve 30 days in jail or to pay a $100 fine. One man paid a fine, but the remaining nine \u2014 eight of whom were Friendship students \u2014chose to take the sentence of 30 days hard labor at the York County Prison Farm. Their choosing jail over a fine or bail marked a first in the Civil Rights Movement since the 1960 Nashville sit-ins, and it sparked the \"jail, no bail\" strategy that came to be emulated in other places. A growing number of people<ref>{{cite news |title=Negroes Open New Front |author=Associated Press |newspaper=St. Petersburg Independent |date=February 9, 1961 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hz9QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M1cDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7379,1465317&dq=rock+hill+sit-in&hl=en |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=In Rock Hill, SC, 150 Negroes and a white man staged a mass protest against segregation.}}</ref> participated in the sit-ins and marches that continued in Rock Hill through the spring<ref>{{cite news |title=Sumpter Sit-in Case Up |author=Associated Press |newspaper=The Sumter Daily |date=November 12, 1962 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=l30wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4KkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4445,3147847&dq=rock+hill+sit-in&hl=en |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=The first case on the court\u2019s agenda involved 65 students from Friendship Junior College at Rock Hill. They were arrested March 15, 1960 for demonstrating in front of the Rock Hill city hall. }}</ref> and into the summer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rock Hill Negro Convicted on Sit-in Charges |author= |newspaper=The News and Courier |date=July 15, 1960 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=op5IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UwsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4617,2282636&dq=rock+hill+sit-in&hl=en |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=Arthur Hamm, recent graduate of Friendship College here, and a demonstration leader, did not appear in city court\u2026.Hamm was arrested with the Rev. A.C. Ivory\u2026. }}</ref>\n\n==Prison strikes==\nSince these protestors chose prison instead of bail, they were sent to a work camp, where twice they refused to work, were put on bread and water as punishment.<ref>{{cite news |title=8 Jailed Negroes Put In Solitary; Refuse To Work |author= |newspaper=The Free Lance-Star |date=February 20, 1961 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HvdNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IYsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4432,2889166&dq=rock+hill+sit-in&hl=en |accessdate=December 1, 2010 |quote=Eight Negro students jailed in a Rock Hill, S. C. sit-in demonstration have been placed on bread and water in solitary confinement for what prison officials called a refusal to work. }}</ref>\n\n==The nine==\nIn 2007 the city of Rock Hill unveiled an historic marker honoring the Friendship Nine at a reception honoring the men. At that time, eight of the Friendship Nine were living.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.heraldonline.com/smedia/2007/01/27/15/friendshipnine.source.prod_affiliate.6.mov |title=Historic marker unveiled by Friendship Nine |author=Justin McGuire |date=January 27, 2007 |publisher=Herald Online |accessdate=December 2, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n* Robert McCullough (died on August 7, 2006)\n* John Gaines\n* Thomas Gaither (at the time, he was a field secretary with the [[Congress of Racial Equality]] and was the only one of the nine who was not a Friendship student)\n* Clarence Graham (died on March 25, 2016)\n* Willie Thomas [W.T. \"Dub\"] Massey (is now a Substitute teacher in the Rock Hill area)<ref>{{cite web|last=Dys|first=Andrew|title=Rock Hill civil rights icon tells young people: \u2018Be great\u2019|url=http://www.heraldonline.com/2013/01/18/4553647/friendship-nine-icon-tells-young.html|work=The Rock Hill, SC Herald|publisher=The McClatchy Co|accessdate=15 October 2013}}</ref> \n* Willie McCleod\n* James Wells (died on July 7, 2018<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldonline.com/latest-news/article214550175.html|title='An American hero.' Friendship 9 member and Rock Hill civil rights icon dies|work=heraldonline|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en}}</ref>)\n* David Williamson Jr.\n* Mack Workman\n\n==The significance==\n\"What made the Rock Hill action so timely ... was that it responded to a tactical dilemma that was arising in [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee|SNCC]] discussions across the South: how to avoid the crippling limitations of scarce bail money,\" wrote [[Taylor Branch]] in ''[[America in the King Years|Parting the Waters]],'' his Pulitzer Prize winning account of the Civil Rights Movement. \"The obvious advantage of 'jail, no bail' was that it reversed the financial burden of the protest, costing the demonstrators no cash while obligating the white authorities to pay for jail space and food. The obvious disadvantage was that staying in jail represented a quantum leap in commitment above the old barrier of arrest, lock-up, and bail-out.\"\n\n==Convictions overturned==\nIn 2015, Judge John C. Hayes III (nephew of the original judge who sentenced the Friendship Nine to 30 days jail-time at York County,SC chain-gang) of Rock Hill overturned the convictions of the nine, stating: \"We cannot rewrite history, but we can right history.\" At the same occasion, Prosecutor Kevin Brackett apologized to the eight men still living, who were in court.<ref>{{cite news |author=Mitch Weiss |title=Famed SC civil rights protesters have convictions erased |url=http://www.wjtv.com/story/27958893/famed-sc-civil-rights-protesters-have-convictions-erased |quote= |pages= |work=WJTV News |agency=Associated Press |date=January 2015 |accessdate=2015-01-28 }}</ref> The men were represented at the hearing by [[Ernest A. Finney, Jr.]], the same lawyer who had defended them originally, who subsequently went on to become the first African-American Chief Justice of the [[South Carolina Supreme Court]] since [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Amber Payne |title='Friendship Nine': Convictions Overturned For Famed Civil Rights Protesters |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/nbcblk/friendship-nine-convictions-overturned-famed-civil-rights-protesters-n295291 |quote= |pages= |work=NBC News |agency=Associated Press |date=January 28, 2015 |accessdate=2015-01-28 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://media.heraldonline.com/smedia/2007/01/27/15/friendshipnine.source.prod_affiliate.6.mov Heraldonline video of historic marker ceremony in 2007]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jVGW9JxTJK8 Civil Rights History Project: Thomas Walter Gaither], video 2:11:06, Library of Congress\n\n{{Civil rights movement}} \n\n[[Category:1961 in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:1961 in American politics]]\n[[Category:Civil rights protests in the United States]]\n[[Category:Civil disobedience]]\n[[Category:History of South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Overturned convictions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Rock Hill, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:McCrory Stores]]\n[[Category:History of African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:Lunch counters]]\n", "name_user": "208.104.49.200", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eOngoing demonstrations)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friendship_Nine"}
{"title_page": "Lauren Miller Rogen", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name               = Lauren Miller \n| image              = Lauren Miller @ 69th Annual Golden Globes Awards.jpg\n| caption            = Miller at the [[69th Golden Globe Awards]] in 2012\n| image_size         = 220px\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1982|7|24}}\n| birth_name         = Lauren Anne Miller\n| birth_place        = [[Lakeland, Florida]], U.S.\n| nationality        = [[Americans|American]]\n| education          = [[Lois Cowles Harrison Center for the Visual and Performing Arts|Harrison School for the Arts]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Florida State University]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = {{flatlist| \n* Actress\n* screenwriter \n* director \n}}\n| yearsactive        = 2003\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Seth Rogen]]|2011}}\n}}\n\n'''Lauren Anne Miller''' (born July 24, 1982)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/IamLaurenMiller/status/660339707474145280|title=@FamousBirthdays 7/24!|first=Lauren Miller|last=Simone|date=October 30, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> is an American actress, [[screenwriter]], and director. She has appeared in the films ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), ''[[Zack and Miri Make a Porno]]'' (2008) and ''[[50/50 (2011 film)|50/50]]'' (2011). In 2012, she starred in the film ''[[For a Good Time, Call...]]'', which she also co-wrote and produced, and in 2018 made her directorial debut with ''[[Like Father]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nMiller was raised in Lakeland, Florida.<ref>Serebrin, Tammy (February 2, 2012). [http://www.theledger.com/article/20120202/NEWS/120209872 \"Harrison Grad's Film Was Shown at Sundance, Likely Headed to Theaters\"]. ''[[The Ledger]]''.</ref> She is the daughter of Adele and Scott Miller, and has a brother, Danny.<ref>Tuschman, Sari Anne [http://la-confidential-magazine.com/living/articles/seth-rogen-alzheimers-hilarity-for-charity \"Good Cause: Seth Rogen's Hilarity for Charity\"]. ''[[Los Angeles Confidential]]''. Retrieved September 7, 2012.</ref> Miller is [[Jewish]].<ref>Schleier, Curt (August 31, 2012). [http://blogs.forward.com/the-arty-semite/162000/ari-graynor-on-jewish-mothers-and-phone-sex/ \"Ari Graynor on Jewish Mothers and Phone Sex\"]. ''[[The Jewish Daily Forward]]''.</ref><ref>Fox, Rachel (September 4, 2012). [https://archive.is/20130204221943/http://twitchfilm.com/interviews/2012/09/jamie-travis-interview.php \"For a Good Time, Call... Director Jamie Travis for a Quickie Chat\"]. [[Twitch Film]].</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.jweekly.com/2010/10/22/schwimmers-secret-wedding-another-new-jewish-couple/|title=Schwimmer\u2019s secret wedding, Another new Jewish couple, \u2026|last=Bloom|first=Nate|date=October 22, 2010|work=[[J. The Jewish News of Northern California]]|access-date=May 21, 2018|language=}}</ref> Miller attended the [[Lois Cowles Harrison Center for the Visual and Performing Arts]] for High School.\n\nIn 2003, Miller graduated from the [[Florida State University College of Motion Picture Arts]]. It was there that she met Katie Anne Naylon, the college roommate with whom Miller would later co-write ''[[For a Good Time, Call...]]'', based on their personal experiences.<ref>Goldstein, Meredith (August 25, 2012). [https://archive.is/20130119021818/http://articles.boston.com/2012-08-25/movies/33339251_1_big-screen-lauren-miller-comedy \"Ari Graynor has a lot on the line\"]. [[Boston.com]].</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAt the beginning of her career, Miller performed supporting roles in several of Seth Rogen's films, including ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'', ''[[Zack and Miri Make A Porno]]'', ''[[Observe and Report]]'', and ''[[50/50 (2011 film)|50/50]]''.<ref>Vineyard, Jennifer (August 28, 2012). [http://www.vulture.com/2012/08/for-a-good-time-call-lauren-miller-interview.html \"Lauren Miller on Her Phone-Sex Comedy and Being a Struggling Actress Married to Seth Rogen\"]. ''[[New York Magazine|Vulture]]''.</ref>\n\nHer first leading film role was opposite [[Ari Graynor]] in the comedy that Miller co-wrote and produced, ''[[For a Good Time, Call...]]''. [[Rolling Stone]] quipped, \"In a rare instance of truth in advertising, the movie actually is a good time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/for-a-good-time-call-20120830|title=For a Good Time, Call...|publisher=}}</ref> [[Focus Features]] picked up the rights to the film at the [[2012 Sundance Film Festival]] for about $2 million<ref>Ryzik, Melena (August 29, 2012). [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/30/movies/for-a-good-time-call-finds-humor-in-phone-sex.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all \"These Women Don\u2019t Blush While Earning Their Rent\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref> and released it in the United States on August 31, 2012. Miller also had a recurring role on the [[FOX]] comedy ''[[Ben and Kate]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nMiller began dating actor [[Seth Rogen]] in 2004. They were engaged on September 29, 2010, and married on October 2, 2011.<ref>D'Zurilla, Christie (October 3, 2011). [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2011/10/seth-rogen-wedding-married-lauren-miller-wedding.html \"Seth Rogen marries Lauren Miller in wine country wedding\"]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2003 || ''Leaving Baghdad'' || || Short film; Producer and editor\n|-\n| 2003 || ''Happy Holidays'' || || Short film; Director and writer\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Straw Hat'' || || Short film; Costume Designer\n|-\n| 2004 || ''My People the Manatee'' || || Short film; Producer\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Measure of Love'' || || Short film; Director and writer\n|-\n| 2005 || ''The Unseen Kind-Hearted Beast'' || || Short film; Producer\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Monster House (film)|Monster House]]'' || || Assistant to [[Steve Starkey]]\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Beowulf (2007 film)|Beowulf]]'' || || Assistant to [[Steve Starkey]]\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' || Scarlett Brighton || \n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Zack and Miri Make a Porno]]'' || Moaner and Groaner || \n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Observe and Report]]'' || Trina || \n|-\n| 2010 || ''The Josh and Adam Show: Beach Day'' || Science Girl #1 || Short film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Girls! Girls! Girls!'' || || Writer\n|-\n| 2011 ||''[[50/50 (2011 film)|50/50]]'' || Bodie || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''Long Black Lashes'' || Courtney || Short film\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[For a Good Time, Call...]]'' || Lauren Powell || Writer and producer\n|-\n| 2012 || ''The Perfect Fit'' || || Short film; Co-writer\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Someone Marry Barry]]'' || Leslie - Speed Dater || \n|-\n| 2014 || ''Growing Up and Other Lies'' || Emma || \n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Sausage Party]]'' || Camille Toh, tampon || Voice role\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Like Father]]'' || Tired Woman || Director, writer, and producer\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Blimp Prom'' || Jenny || TV Movie\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Ben and Kate]]'' || Darcy || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Inside Edition]]'' || Herself || Episode dated 27 February 2014\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' || Judy || Season 12, Episode 10  \n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Master of None]]'' || Christine || Season 2, Episode 4 \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Lauren Miller}}\n* {{IMDb name|1601643|Lauren Miller}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller Rogen, Lauren}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lakeland, Florida]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Florida]]\n[[Category:Florida State University alumni]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American women film producers]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Florida]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name               = Lauren Miller \n| image              = Lauren Miller @ 69th Annual Golden Globes Awards.jpg\n| caption            = Miller at the [[69th Golden Globe Awards]] in 2012\n| image_size         = 220px\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1982|7|24}}\n| birth_name         = Lauren Anne Miller\n| birth_place        = [[Lakeland, Florida]], U.S.\n| nationality        = [[Americans|American]]\n| education          = [[Lois Cowles Harrison Center for the Visual and Performing Arts|Harrison School for the Arts]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Florida State University]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = {{flatlist| \n* Actress\n* screenwriter \n* director \n}}\n| yearsactive        = 2003\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Seth Rogen]]|2011}}\n}}\n\n'''Lauren Anne Miller''' (born July 24, 1982)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/IamLaurenMiller/status/660339707474145280|title=@FamousBirthdays 7/24!|first=Lauren Miller|last=Simone|date=October 30, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> is an American actress, [[screenwriter]], and director. She has appeared in the films ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), ''[[Zack and Miri Make a Porno]]'' (2008) and ''[[50/50 (2011 film)|50/50]]'' (2011). In 2012, she starred in the film ''[[For a Good Time, Call...]]'', which she also co-wrote and produced, and in 2018 made her directorial debut with ''[[Like Father]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nMiller was raised in Lakeland, Florida.<ref>Serebrin, Tammy (February 2, 2012). [http://www.theledger.com/article/20120202/NEWS/120209872 \"Harrison Grad's Film Was Shown at Sundance, Likely Headed to Theaters\"]. ''[[The Ledger]]''.</ref> She is the daughter of Adele and Scott Miller, and has a brother, Danny.<ref>Tuschman, Sari Anne [http://la-confidential-magazine.com/living/articles/seth-rogen-alzheimers-hilarity-for-charity \"Good Cause: Seth Rogen's Hilarity for Charity\"]. ''[[Los Angeles Confidential]]''. Retrieved September 7, 2012.</ref> Miller is [[Jewish]].<ref>Schleier, Curt (August 31, 2012). [http://blogs.forward.com/the-arty-semite/162000/ari-graynor-on-jewish-mothers-and-phone-sex/ \"Ari Graynor on Jewish Mothers and Phone Sex\"]. ''[[The Jewish Daily Forward]]''.</ref><ref>Fox, Rachel (September 4, 2012). [https://archive.is/20130204221943/http://twitchfilm.com/interviews/2012/09/jamie-travis-interview.php \"For a Good Time, Call... Director Jamie Travis for a Quickie Chat\"]. [[Twitch Film]].</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.jweekly.com/2010/10/22/schwimmers-secret-wedding-another-new-jewish-couple/|title=Schwimmer\u2019s secret wedding, Another new Jewish couple, \u2026|last=Bloom|first=Nate|date=October 22, 2010|work=[[J. The Jewish News of Northern California]]|access-date=May 21, 2018|language=}}</ref> Miller attended the [[Lois Cowles Harrison Center for the Visual and Performing Arts]] for High School.\n\nMiller graduated from the film school at [[Florida State University]]. It was there that she met Katie Anne Naylon, the college roommate with whom Miller would later co-write ''[[For a Good Time, Call...]]'', based on their personal experiences.<ref>Goldstein, Meredith (August 25, 2012). [https://archive.is/20130119021818/http://articles.boston.com/2012-08-25/movies/33339251_1_big-screen-lauren-miller-comedy \"Ari Graynor has a lot on the line\"]. [[Boston.com]].</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAt the beginning of her career, Miller performed supporting roles in several of Seth Rogen's films, including ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'', ''[[Zack and Miri Make A Porno]]'', ''[[Observe and Report]]'', and ''[[50/50 (2011 film)|50/50]]''.<ref>Vineyard, Jennifer (August 28, 2012). [http://www.vulture.com/2012/08/for-a-good-time-call-lauren-miller-interview.html \"Lauren Miller on Her Phone-Sex Comedy and Being a Struggling Actress Married to Seth Rogen\"]. ''[[New York Magazine|Vulture]]''.</ref>\n\nHer first leading film role was opposite [[Ari Graynor]] in the comedy that Miller co-wrote and produced, ''[[For a Good Time, Call...]]''. [[Rolling Stone]] quipped, \"In a rare instance of truth in advertising, the movie actually is a good time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/for-a-good-time-call-20120830|title=For a Good Time, Call...|publisher=}}</ref> [[Focus Features]] picked up the rights to the film at the [[2012 Sundance Film Festival]] for about $2 million<ref>Ryzik, Melena (August 29, 2012). [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/30/movies/for-a-good-time-call-finds-humor-in-phone-sex.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all \"These Women Don\u2019t Blush While Earning Their Rent\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref> and released it in the United States on August 31, 2012. Miller also had a recurring role on the [[FOX]] comedy ''[[Ben and Kate]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nMiller began dating actor [[Seth Rogen]] in 2004. They were engaged on September 29, 2010, and married on October 2, 2011.<ref>D'Zurilla, Christie (October 3, 2011). [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2011/10/seth-rogen-wedding-married-lauren-miller-wedding.html \"Seth Rogen marries Lauren Miller in wine country wedding\"]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2003 || ''Leaving Baghdad'' || || Short film; Producer and editor\n|-\n| 2003 || ''Happy Holidays'' || || Short film; Director and writer\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Straw Hat'' || || Short film; Costume Designer\n|-\n| 2004 || ''My People the Manatee'' || || Short film; Producer\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Measure of Love'' || || Short film; Director and writer\n|-\n| 2005 || ''The Unseen Kind-Hearted Beast'' ||